of modernism that resulted from the rise of National Socialism. Weimar Germany and its culture, with its meld of eighteenth-century German classicism and twentieth-century modernism, served as a touchstone for this group of diverse talents and opinions.Weimar on the Pacific is the first book to examine these artists and intellectuals as a group. Ehrhard Bahr studies selected works of Adorno, Horkheimer, Brecht, Lang, Neutra, Schindler, Döblin, Mann, and Schoenberg, weighing Los Angeles’s influence on them and their impact on German modernism. Touching on such examples as film noir and Thomas Mann’s Doctor Faustus, Bahr shows how this community of exiles reconstituted modernism in the face of the traumatic political and historical changes they were living through.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGermanszCaliforniaxIntellectual life. 0aGermanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxIntellectual life. 0aJews, GermanzCaliforniaxIntellectual life. 0aJews, GermanzCaliforniazLos AngelesxIntellectual life. 0aModernism (Aesthetics)zCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aModernism (Aesthetics)zCalifornia. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh  a18th century.  a1930s.  a1940s.  a20th century.  aamerican history.  aarnold schoenberg.  abertolt brecht.  acalifornia.  aclassicism.  aehrhard bahr.  aexile.  afritz lang.  agerman artists.  agerman modernism.  agermany.  aintellectual.  alos angeles.  amodernism.  anational socialism.  apacific coast.  aschoenberg.  asocialism.  asouthern california.  atheodore adorno.  athomas mann.  aunited states history.  aus history.  aweimer germany.  aweimer republic.  awest coast.  awestern united states.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Pre